          "body": "The chapter closes with the most haunting image in the Pentateuch: *The LORD will bring you back to Egypt in ships... and there you will offer yourselves for sale to your enemies as male and female slaves, but there will be no buyer.* The foundational redemptive event of Israel's existence — the exodus from Egyptian slavery — is reversed. Israel returns to Egypt, voluntarily offering herself as a slave, and is rejected even there. Geographically, theologically, redemptively, the curse undoes the exodus. This is where the New Testament's gospel cuts in. Galatians 3:13 announces: *Christ redeemed us from the curse of the Law, having become a curse for us — for it is written, 'Cursed is everyone who hangs on a tree.'* Every curse of Deuteronomy 28 — confusion, disease, defeat, dispersion, dread, the iron yoke, the reversed exodus — fell on the Substitute at Golgotha. The Crucified One absorbed the entire weight of this chapter so that the covenant blessings of vv.1-14 could flow to all who are united to Him by faith (Galatians 3:14)."
